{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14892"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0.03,0.02,0.85]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59210"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4407"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59210"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic at 28 weeks gestation with increasing fatigue and episodes of presyncope over the past two weeks. She has been taking oral iron supplements for the past six weeks but reports significant nausea and poor compliance. She has no other medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears pale but well. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Investigations reveal: haemoglobin 92 g/L (105-145), mean cell volume 75 fL (80-100), ferritin 8 mcg/L (30-200), transferrin saturation 8% (20-50).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence twice daily oral iron","Intramuscular iron injection","Continue oral iron and review in two weeks","Red cell transfusion","Intravenous iron infusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic iron deficiency anaemia in pregnancy that has not responded adequately to oral iron therapy. The combination of low haemoglobin, low mean cell volume, very low ferritin, and low transferrin saturation confirms iron deficiency as the cause. Poor compliance with oral iron due to side effects is a common problem in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous iron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step given the poor response to and intolerance of oral iron, the severity of symptoms, and the relatively advanced gestational age. Modern preparations such as ferric carboxymaltose are safe in pregnancy and can rapidly correct iron deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue oral iron\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the documented poor compliance and ongoing symptoms. There is insufficient time remaining in the pregnancy to correct the anaemia with this approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwice daily oral iron\u003C/strong\u003E would likely worsen the gastrointestinal side effects without improving absorption. In fact, splitting the dose may reduce overall iron absorption as it becomes saturated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular iron\u003C/strong\u003E injections are painful, require multiple doses, and have unpredictable absorption. They have largely been superseded by intravenous preparations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for this level of anaemia in a haemodynamically stable patient. Transfusion is typically reserved for severe anaemia (haemoglobin \u0026lt;70 g/L) or acute blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIron deficiency anaemia in pregnancy is associated with increased risk of preterm birth, low birth weight, and postpartum depression. Prompt correction is important, particularly in the third trimester when fetal iron demands are highest and there is limited time remaining before delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous iron should be considered in pregnancy when oral iron is not tolerated or ineffective, or when rapid correction is needed.","Iron deficiency anaemia in pregnancy is defined as haemoglobin \u003C110 g/L in first trimester or \u003C105 g/L in second and third trimesters.","Ferritin \u003C30 mcg/L indicates iron deficiency in pregnancy."],"references":["Govindappagari S, Burwick RM. Treatment of Iron Deficiency Anemia in Pregnancy with Intravenous versus Oral Iron: Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Am J Perinatol. 2019 Mar;36(4):366-376. doi: 10.1055/s-0038-1668555. Epub 2018 Aug 19. PMID: 30121943."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14892"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T15:53:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T15:58:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"typ